data.content:
Here's the modernized version:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void CreateUser_NullEmail_ThrowsException()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    Assert.ThrowsExactly<ArgumentNullException>(() => service.CreateUser(null, "John"));
}
```

**Key changes:**
1. Remove `[ExpectedException(typeof(...))]` attribute
2. Wrap the throwing call in `Assert.ThrowsExactly<T>(() => ...)`

**Why this is better:**
- Pinpoints *which line* must throw — `[ExpectedException]` passes if *any* line in the method throws, masking bugs
- You can capture the exception to assert on its message/properties:

```csharp
var ex = Assert.ThrowsExactly<ArgumentNullException>(() => service.CreateUser(null, "John"));
Assert.AreEqual("email", ex.ParamName);
```

> **Note:** `ThrowsExactly` requires an exact type match. If you want to allow derived exception types, use `Assert.ThrowsException<T>` instead. `ThrowsExactly` was introduced in MSTest v3.

